Install the required packages:

# zypper in adcli sssd sssd-ldap sssd-ad sssd-tools
Configure sssd.conf:

Example configuration of file /etc/sssd/sssd.conf

[sssd]
config_file_version = 2
services = nss,pam
domains = example.com

[nss]
filter_users = root
filter_groups = root

[pam]

[domain/example.com]
id_provider = ad
auth_provider = ad
ad_domain = example.com
cache_credentials = true
enumerate = false
override_homedir = /home/%d/%u
ldap_id_mapping = true
ldap_referrals = false
ldap_schema = ad
Configure NSS:

example:

[sssd]
config_file_version = 2
services = nss,pam
use_fully_qualified_names = true
domains = QHIS.LOCAL
default_domain_suffix = QHIS.LOCAL
 
[nss]
filter_users = root
filter_groups = root
 
[pam]
 
[domain/QHIS.LOCAL]
id_provider = ad
auth_provider = ad
ad_domain = QHIS.LOCAL
cache_credentials = true
enumerate = false
override_homedir = /home/%d/%u
ldap_id_mapping = true
ldap_referrals = false
ldap_schema = ad
access_provider = simple
simple_allow_groups = QHIS-vmpspprweb02-SSH-ACCESS@QHIS.LOCAL

Example parameters in /etc/nsswitch.conf:

passwd: compat sss
group: compat sss
Create the computer account and join to the domain (AD user must be able to create computer accounts):

# adcli join -D example.com
Password for [Administrator@](<mailto:Administrator@EXAMPLE.COM>)EXAMPLE.COM:
Enable and start the SSSD daemon:

# systemctl enable sssd
# systemctl start sssd
Configure PAM:

Enable using pam-config:

# pam-config -a --sss
# pam-config -a --mkhomedir
